# Adjudication of the fixed specification curve

The NSW experiment yields a treated-minus-control benchmark of $1,794 in 1978 earnings (95% CI not used as the reference here). Replacing its controls with all 15,992 CPS controls produces a naive observational difference of $-8,498 (95% CI [$-9,641, $-7,354]), a gap of $-10,292 from the experimental result. Thus the raw CPS comparison is not a credible substitute for the randomized control group.

The eight adjusted estimates do not deliver robust recovery. Across the fixed curve, estimates range from $-4,162 to $1,759, and their gaps from the benchmark range from $-5,956 to $-36. 3 of 8 adjusted 95% intervals include the experimental benchmark. The closest point estimate is the Demographics + earnings; trimmed; 1-NN matching specification ($1,759; gap $-36; 95% CI [$189, $3,328]). That pattern is best described as favorable-specification-only recovery rather than a general success or a blanket failure of propensity-score adjustment.

The design details matter substantively. Each propensity score is a main-effects logit fitted once on the full NSW-treated/CPS-control composite. The trimmed specifications retain only observations lying in the intersection of the treated and control ranges of those already-fitted scores; they therefore change the ATT target population as well as the sample. Nearest-neighbor estimates target the retained treated group using replacement, while subclassification contrasts five treated-score quintiles and weights them by treated counts. Their intervals use different transparent approximations: a control-reuse CR1 interval for matching conditional on fitted scores, and a Neyman fixed-strata interval for subclassification. Neither interval repairs bias from a bad comparison group.

The retained counts also make the support issue concrete. Demographics-only trimming retains all 185 treated participants but removes CPS observations outside their score range; the earnings specification produces a more selective control comparison. Because no treated cases are removed in this run, the treated target remains numerically unchanged, but that is an empirical feature of these fitted scores rather than a guarantee of the procedure. In another application, intersection trimming could remove treated people and alter the estimand more directly.

A paper may therefore say that some prespecified combinations of earnings covariates, support restriction, and propensity-score estimator bring the CPS comparison closer to the experimental result. It may not say, without qualification, that propensity-score methods recover the experimental effect. Conditional ignorability is an untestable assumption here: observed demographics and prior earnings can balance measured composition, but cannot rule out unobserved labor-market history, motivation, local conditions, or selection into the CPS pool. Moreover, trimming can make a closer estimate apply only to treated people in common fitted-score support, not necessarily to all NSW participants. The curve supports Smith and Todd's fragility concern: apparent recovery depends on analytic choices and should be reported as sensitivity evidence, not as validation of the observational design.
